The cuticle contains 
five types
of areole distributed all over the cuticle (
Figure 2B
). Simple areoles (
Figure 2B–D
) are the most abundant, and are flat and rectangular in shape with a warty surface (blackberry-like). These areoles are transversal to the longitudinal axis of the body. Among these are scattered tubercle areoles of the same shape but with very long tubercles (
12.6 mm
) on top (
Figure 2D, E
). Bulging areoles are isolated or form clusters of two, three, or four areoles (
Figure 2C, D
). These areoles are taller (
5.2 mm
) than the simple areoles, with a pyramid form and small bristles on the top. Crowned areoles (
Figure 2B, F
) occur in pairs, have moderately short filaments on top, and are surrounded by about 17–24 circumcluster areoles. These circumcluster areoles are the tallest (
20.5– 23.8 mm
), being conical, with a ring of short filaments at the apex and curved towards the centre (
Figure 2B, E, F
).

